Problem: cindy has her eye on a sundress but thinks it is too expensive . it goes on sale for 15 % less than the original price . before cindy can buy the dress , however , the store raises the new price by 25 % . if the dress cost $ 51 after it went on sale for 15 % off , what is the difference between the original price and the final price ?
student_process: Original price: $x$ final price: $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x=51 \div(1-0.15)=60 \\ & y=51 \times(1+0.25)=63.75 \\ & y-x=63.75-60=3.75 \end{aligned} $$

student_process: discounts rates of pony jeans is $X \%$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 15 \times 3 \times(1-(22 \%-x \%))+20 \times 2 \times(1-x \%)=15 \times 3+20 \times 2-9 \\ & 45 \times(22-x) \%+40 \times x \%=9 \\ & 45 \times(22-x)+40 x=900 \\ & 5 x=90 \\ & x=18 \end{aligned} $$

student_process: machine a manufacture a sprockets per hour , machine $b$ manufacture $b$ sprockets per hour $t$ hours for machine $b$ to manufacture 550 sprocket. $$ \begin{aligned} & b=1.1 a \\ & a(t+10)=b t \\ & a t+10 a=1.1 a t=550 \\ & 10 a=0.1 a t \\ & 100 a=a t \\ & 110 a=550 \\ & a=50 . \end{aligned} $$

student_process: t is time for machine $b$ to make 20 widgets. $(t+2) \times 2$ is time for machine $r$ to make 40 widgets $$ \begin{aligned} & 3 \times\left(\frac{20}{t}+\frac{20}{t+2}\right)=25 \\ & 25 t^2+50 t=120 t+120 \\ & 5 t^2-14 t-24=0 \\ & t=-\frac{6}{5}, 4 \\ & (t+2) \times 4=6 \times 4=24 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: two trains , a and b , started simultaneously from opposite ends of a 200 - mile route and traveled toward each other on parallel tracks . train a , traveling at a constant rate , completed the 200 - mile trip in 10 hours ; train b , traveling at a constant rate , completed the 200 - mile trip in 6 hours . how many miles had train a traveled when it met train b ?

the area of one square is x ^ 2 + 12 x + 36 and the area of another square is 4 x ^ 2  12 x + 9 . if the sum of the perimeters of both squares is 64 , what is the value of x ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & x^2+12 x+36 \\ = & (x+6)^2 \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow(x+6)$ is the length of one side $$ \begin{aligned} & 4 x^2-12 x+9 \\ & =(2 x-3)^2 \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow(2 x-3)$ is the length of one side. $$ \begin{aligned} & 4(x+6)+4(2 x-3)=64 \\ & \because 4 \\ & \Rightarrow(x+6)+(2 x-3)=16 \\ & \Rightarrow 3 x+3=16 \\ & \Rightarrow 3 x=13 \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{13}{3} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: an electric pump can fill a tank in 4 hours . because of a leak in the tank , it took 8 hours to fill the tank . if the tank is full , how much time will the leak take to empty it ?
student_process: Assume the electric pump fill $x$ liter per hour \& the tank empty $y$ liter per hour $$ \begin{aligned} & 4 x=8(x-y) \\ \Rightarrow & 4 x=8 x-8 y \\ \Rightarrow & 4 x=8 y \\ \Rightarrow & x=2 y \\ \because & x=2 y \\ \therefore & 4 x=8 y \end{aligned} $$

the average of 10 consecutive integers is 15 . then , 9 is deducted from the first consecutive number , 8 is deducted from the second , 7 is deducted form the third , and so on until the last number which remains unchanged . what is the new average ?
student_process: Assume the 10 consecutive integers is $x_1, x_2, x_3, \cdots, x_{10}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 15 \times 10=150 \\ & \Rightarrow\left(x_1+x_2+x_3+\cdots+x_{10}\right)=150 \\ & 150-(9+8+7+6+\cdots+2+1) \\ & =150-45 \\ & =105 \\ & 105 \div 10=10.5  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: 5 % of a number is more than 20 % of 650 by 190 . find the number ?

Problem: if 15 % of 40 is greater than 25 % of a number by 2 , then the number is ?

Problem: arnold and danny are two twin brothers that are celebrating their birthday . the product of their ages today is smaller by 17 from the product of their ages a year from today . what is their age today ?
student_process: Assume they are $x$ years old. $$ \begin{aligned} & x^2+17=(x+1)^2 \\ \Rightarrow & x^2+17=x^2+2 x+1 \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x+1=17 \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x=16 \\ \Rightarrow & x=16 \div 2=8 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if a person has two rectangular fields . the larger field has thrice the length and 4 times the width of the smaller field . if the smaller field has a length 50 % more than the width . if a person takes 20 minutes to complete one round of a smaller field then what is the time required to complete one round of a larger field ?
student_process: Assume the width of the smaller field is $x$ the length of the smaller field is $1.5 x$ the length of the larger field is $4.5 x$ the with of the larger field is $4 X$ the area of the smaller field $$ \Rightarrow x \cdot 1.5 x=1.5 x^2 $$ the area of the larger field $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 4.5 x \cdot 4 x=18 x^2 \\ & 18 x^2 \div 1.5 x^2=12 \\ & 20 \times 12=240 \text { miss }  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a can do a piece of work in 4 hours . a and c together can do it in just 2 hours , while b and c together need 3 hours to finish the same work . b alone can complete the work in - - - hours .
student_process: Assume the workload is $x$ a can finish $\frac{x}{4}$ per hour. $$ \left[x-\left(\frac{x}{4} \times 2\right)\right] \div 2=\left(\frac{1}{2} x\right) \div 2=\frac{1}{4} x $$ $\Rightarrow c$ can finish $\frac{x}{4}$ per hour. $$ \left[x-\left(\frac{x}{4} \times 3\right)\right] \div 3=\left(\frac{1}{4} x\right) \div 3=\frac{1}{12} x $$ $\Rightarrow b$ can finish $\frac{x}{12}$ per hour. $\therefore b$ can finish alone in 12 hours

Problem: on the independence day , bananas were be equally distributed among the children in a school so that each child would get two bananas . on the particular day 305 children were absent and as a result each child got two extra bananas . find the actual number of children in the school ?
student_process: Assume the actual number of children is $\chi$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 2 x=4(x-305) \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x=4 x-1220 \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x=1220 \\ \Rightarrow & x=1220 \div 2=610 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: find the principle on a certain sum of money at 5 % per annum for 2 2 / 5 years if the amount being rs . 1904 ?

Problem: a candidate got 30 % of the votes polled and he lost to his rival by 4000 votes . how many votes were cast ?
student_process: Assume the votes is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 1-30 \%=70 \%=0.7 \\ & 0.7 x-4000=0.3 x \\ & \Rightarrow 0.4 x=4000 \\ & \Rightarrow x=400 \div 0.4=10000 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a mixture of 200 liters of wine and water contains 20 % water . how much more water should be added so that water becomes 25 % of the new mixture ?
student_process: Assume added $X$ liters water $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(200 \times 0,2+x)}{200+x}=25 \% \\ & \Rightarrow 40+x=0,25(200+x) \\ & \Rightarrow 40+x=50+\frac{1}{4} x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{3}{4} x=50-40=10 \\ & \Rightarrow x=10 \div \frac{3}{4}=\frac{40}{3} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a candidate got 35 % of the votes and lost to the rival by 1800 votes . how many votes were cast ?
student_process: Assume the votes is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 1-35 \%=65 \%=0.65 \\ & 0.65 x-1800=0.35 x \\ & \Rightarrow 0.65 x-0.35 x=1800 \\ & \Rightarrow 0.3 x=1800 \\ & \Rightarrow x=1800 \div 0.3=6000 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a works twice as fast as b . if b can complete a work in 12 days independently , the number of days in which a and b can together finish the work in :
student_process: Assume the workload is $x$ $b$ can finish $\frac{x}{12}$ per day. $$ \frac{x}{12} \times 2=\frac{x}{6} $$ $\Rightarrow$ a can finish $\frac{x}{6}$ per day. $$ \frac{x}{12}+\frac{x}{6}=\frac{3 x}{12}=\frac{x}{4} $$ $\because \frac{x}{4} \cdot 4=x$ together $\therefore$ they can finish together in 4 days.

a certain list consists of 21 different numbers . if n is in the list and n is 4 times the average ( arithmetic mean ) of the other 20 numbers in the list , then n is what fraction e of the sum of the 21 numbers in the list ?
student_process: average of the other 20 numbers in the list is $\frac{(e-n)}{20}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & n=4 \times \frac{(e-n)}{20} \\ \Rightarrow & n=\frac{(e-n)}{5} \\ \Rightarrow & n+\frac{1}{5} n=\frac{e}{5} \\ \Rightarrow & \frac{6}{5} n=\frac{1}{5} e \\ \Rightarrow & n=\left(\frac{1}{5} e\right) \times \frac{5}{6}=\frac{1}{6} e \end{aligned} $$

Problem: p , q and r together earn rs . 1980 in 9 days . p and r can earn rs . 600 in 5 days . q and r in 7 days can earn rs . 910 . how much amount does r can earn per day ?
student_process: $$ 1980 \div 9=220 $$ $\Rightarrow p, q, r$ together earn per day. $$ 600 \div 5=120 $$ $\Rightarrow p, r$ can earn per day. $$ 910 \div 7=130 $$ $\Rightarrow q, r$ can earn per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & 220-120-130=-30 \\ & \Rightarrow(p, q, r)-(p, r)-(q, r)=-r \\ & -30=-r \\ & \Rightarrow r=30

Problem: linda spent 3 / 4 of her savings on furniture and the rest on a tv . if the tv cost her $ 400 , what were her original savings ?

Problem: two trains leave the train station at the same time . one train , on the blue line , heads east - while the other , on the red line , heads west . if the train on the blue line averages 40 km / hr and the other train averages 40 km / hr - how long will it take for the trains to be 100 km apart ?

Problem: if 3 girls can do 3 times of a particular work in 3 days , then , 7 girls can do 7 times of that work in

at a certain high school , the senior class is 3 times the size of the junior class . if 1 / 3 of the seniors and 3 / 4 of the juniors study japanese , what fraction of the students in both classes study japanese ?
student_process: Assume the number of the junior class is $X$. the total number is $(x+3 x)=4 x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \left(3 x \cdot \frac{1}{3}\right)+\frac{3}{4} x=x+\frac{1}{4} x=\frac{7}{4} x \\ & \frac{7}{4} x \div 4 x=\frac{7}{4} x \cdot \frac{1}{4 x}=\frac{7}{16} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the length and breadth of a rectangular courtyard is 75 m and 32 m . find the cost of leveling it at the rate of $ 3 per m 2 . also , find the distance covered by a boy to take 4 rounds of the courtyard .

Problem: in track last week , the boys ran 34 laps . the girls ran 20 more laps . each lap is a 1 / 6 th of a mile . how many miles did the girls run ?
if x + 4 y = 5 and 5 x + 6 y = 7 , then 3 x + 5 y = ?
student_process: $$ \left\{\begin{array}{l} x+4 y=5-(1) \\ 5 x+6 y=7-\text { (2) } \end{array}\right. $$ (1) $\times 5$ - (2) $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 14 y=18 \\ & \Rightarrow y=18 \div 14=\frac{9}{7} \\ & y=\frac{9}{7} \text { put into } 10 \\ & \Rightarrow x+\frac{9}{7} \cdot 4=5 \\ & \Rightarrow x+\frac{36}{7}=5 \\ & \Rightarrow x=5-\frac{36}{7}=\frac{-1}{7} \\ & 3 x+5 y=\left(\frac{-1}{7}\right) \times 3+\left(\frac{9}{7}\right) \times 5=\frac{-3}{7}+\frac{45}{7}=\frac{42}{7}=6 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a grocer has a sale of rs . 5124 , rs . 5366 , rs . 5808 , rs . 5399 and rs . 6124 for 5 consecutive months . how much sale must he have in the sixth month so that he gets an average sale of rs . 5400 ?
an amount at compound interest sums to rs . 17640 / - in 2 years and to rs . 22932 / - in 3 years at the same rate of interest . find the rate percentage ?
student_process: Assume the original money is $x$ $\&$ interest rate is $y$ $$ \left\{\begin{array}{l} x \cdot(1+y)^2=17640-0 \\ x \cdot(1+y)^3=22932 \text {-(2) } \end{array}\right. $$ (2) $\div$ (1) $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow(1+y)=\frac{22932}{17640}=\frac{5133}{4410}=\frac{1911}{1470}=\frac{273}{210}=\frac{91}{90} \\ & =\frac{11}{10} \\ & =1,3 \\ & \Rightarrow y=1,3-1=0,3=30 \% \# \\ & \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a runs twice as fast as b and gives b a start of 60 m . how long should the racecourse be so that a and b might reach in the same time ?
student_process: Assume the speed of $b$ is $\chi$ \& they arrive in the same time, the time is $t$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot t+60=(2 x) \cdot t \\ \Rightarrow & x t+60=2 x t \\ \Rightarrow & x t=60 \\ & 60+60=120 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: working alone at its constant rate , machine a produces x boxes in 10 minutes and working alone at its constant rate , machine b produces 2 x boxes in 5 minutes . how many minutes does it take machines a and b , working simultaneously at their respective constant rates , to produce 5 x boxes ?
student_process: $\frac{x}{10} \Rightarrow a$ can produce $\frac{x}{10}$ boxes per minute. $\frac{2 x}{5} \Rightarrow b$ can produce $\frac{2 x}{5}$ boxes per minute. $$ \frac{x}{10}+\frac{2 x}{5}=\frac{5 x}{10}=\frac{x}{2} $$ Assume they work $t$ minutes. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{2} \cdot t=5 x \\ & \Rightarrow t=5 x \div \frac{x}{2}=10  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: ele , the circus elephant , is currently 3 times older than lyn , the circus lion . in 15 years from now , lyn the circus lion will be exactly half as old as ele , the circus elephant . how old is ele today ?
student_process: Assume lyon is currently $x$ years old, $$ \begin{aligned} & (x+15) \times 2=(3 x+15) \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x+30=3 x+15 \\ & \Rightarrow x=30-15=15 \\ & 3 x=15 \times 3=45 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if 20 liters of chemical x are added to 80 liters of a mixture that is 15 % chemical x and 85 % chemical y , then what percentage of the resulting mixture is chemical x ?

a customer bought a product at the shop . however , the shopkeeper increased the price of the product by 20 % so that the customer could not buy the required amount of the product . the customer managed to buy only 80 % of the required amount . what is the difference in the amount of money that the customer paid for the second purchase compared to the first purchase ?
student_process: Assume the original price is $x$ \& the amount which customers was bought is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & {[(1+20 \%) x][80 \% \cdot y]} \\ & =1,2 x \cdot 0.8 y \\ & =0,96 x y \\ & \frac{0.96 \times y}{x y}=\frac{96}{100}=96 \% \\ & 100 \%-96 \%=4 \% \# \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the product of x and y is a constant . if the value of x is increased by 50 % , by what percentage must the value of y be decreased ?
student_process: Assume $x y=k$ $$ \begin{aligned} & {[(1+50 \%) x] y=1,5 x y=1,5 k} \\ & 1,5 k \cdot \frac{2}{3}=k \\ & \Rightarrow y-\frac{2}{3} y=\frac{1}{3} y \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{1}{3} = 33,33 \%  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: 5 years ago , the average age of a and b was 15 years . average age of a , b and c today is 20 years . how old will c be after 14 years ?

Problem: the length of a rectangular floor is more than its breadth by 200 % . if rs . 324 is required to paint the floor at the rate of rs . 3 per sq m , then what would be the length of the floor ?
student_process: Assume the breadth is $\chi$. $\Rightarrow$ the length is $x+2 x=3 x$ $x \cdot 3 x=3 x^2 \Rightarrow$ the area of the rectangular. $$ \begin{aligned} & 3 x^2 \cdot 3=324 \\ \Rightarrow & 3 x^2=324 \div 3=108 \\ \Rightarrow & x^2=108 \div 3=36 \\ \Rightarrow & x=\sqrt{36}=6 \\ & 6 \times 3=18 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: two pots are in side - by - side . one pot , which is 20 inches tall , casts a shadow that is 10 inches long . the other pot is 40 inches tall . compute , in inches , the length of the shadow that the taller pot casts .
student_process: Assume the shadow is $\chi$ inches long. $$ \begin{aligned} & 40 \div 20=2 \\ & 10 \times 2=20 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the pinedale bus line travels at an average speed of 60 km / h , and has stops every 5 minutes along its route . yahya wants to go from his house to the pinedale mall , which is 10 stops away . how far away , in kilometers , is pinedale mall away from yahya ' s house ?
student_process: $5 \times 10=50$ minutes $\Rightarrow$ total travel time. $$ 60 \div 60=1 $$ $\Rightarrow$ travel $1 \mathrm{~km}$ per minute. $$ 1 \times 50=50 \mathrm{~km}  $$

Problem: the difference between the compound interest compounded annually and simple interest for 2 years at 20 % per annum is rs . 432 . find the principal ?
student_process: Assume the money is $x$. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1+20 \%)^2-x \cdot\left[1+\left(20 \% x_2\right)\right]=432 \\ \Rightarrow & 1,44 x-1,4 x=432 \\ \Rightarrow & 0,04 x=432 \\ \Rightarrow & x=432 \div 0,04=10800 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a trained covered x km at 40 kmph and another 2 x km at 20 kmph . find the average speed of the train in covering the entire 6 x km .
student_process: $40 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \rightarrow 2 x$ distance $20 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \rightarrow 4 x$ distance Assume $x=40$ $$ \begin{aligned} 40 \times 2 & =80 \mathrm{~km} \\ 40 \times 4 & =160 \mathrm{~km} \end{aligned} $$ $80 \mathrm{~km} \div 40=2$ $160 \mathrm{~km} \div 20=8$ $2+8=10 \Rightarrow$ total travel hours $$ \frac{2}{10} \times 40+\frac{8}{10} \times 20=8+16=24 \mathrm{~km}  $$

Problem: on thursday mabel handled 90 transactions . anthony handled 10 % more transactions than mabel , cal handled 2 / 3 rds of the transactions that anthony handled , and jade handled 18 more transactions than cal . how much transactions did jade handled ?

when sold at a 60 % discount , a sweater nets the merchant a 20 % profit on the wholesale cost at which he initially purchased the item . by what % is the sweater marked up from wholesale at its normal retail price ?
student_process: Assume the cost is $x \&$ retail price is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 0.6 y=(1+20 \%) x=1.2 x \\ & y=2 x \\ & 2-1=1=100 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a certain sum is invested at simple interest at 18 % p . a . for two years instead of investing at 12 % p . a . for the same time period . therefore the interest received is more by rs . 240 . find the sum ?
student_process: Assume the sum is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot[1+(18 \% \times 2)]-x \cdot[1+(12 \% \times 2)] \\ & =240 \\ & \Rightarrow 1,36 x-1,24 x=240 \\ & \Rightarrow 0,12 x=240 \\ & \Rightarrow x=240 \div 0,12=2000 \end{aligned} $$

student_process: Assume the average score after 11 th is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(x \cdot 11)+75}{12}=x+1 \\ & \Rightarrow 11 x+75=12 x+12 \\ & \Rightarrow x=75-12=63 \\ & 63+1=64  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a leak in the bottom of a tank can empty the full tank in 6 hours . an inlet pipe fills water at the rate of 4 litres a minute . when the tank is full , the inlet is opened and due to the leak the tank is empty in 8 hours . the capacity of the tank ( in litres ) is
student_process: Assume the capacity is $x$ liters $\frac{x}{6} \Rightarrow$ the amount of leakage per hour, $4 \times 60=240 \Rightarrow$ the amount of filling per hour. $$ \begin{aligned} & \left(\frac{x}{6}-240\right) \times 8=x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{4 x}{3}-1920=x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{1}{3} x=1920 \\ & \Rightarrow x=1920 \times 3=5760 \text { liters }  \end{aligned} $$

student_process: Assume be work $x$ hours. $$ \begin{aligned} & 40 \times 16+(x-40) \times(16 \times 1.75)=948 \\ \Rightarrow & 640+28(x-40)=948 \\ \Rightarrow & 28 x-1120=948-640 \\ \Rightarrow & 28 x=308+1120=1428 \\ \Rightarrow & x=1428 \div 28=51  \end{aligned} $$

student_process: Assume after $x$ years $$ \begin{aligned} & 18000-(1200 \cdot x)=42000+(800 \cdot x) \\ \Rightarrow & 18000-1200 x=42000+800 x \\ \Rightarrow & 800 x+1200 x=18000-42000 \\ \Rightarrow & 2000 x=36000 \\ \Rightarrow & x=36000 \div 2000=18 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if 12 men or 20 women can do a piece of work in 54 days , then in how many days can 9 men and 39 women together do the work ?
student_process: Assume a man can finish $x$ per day, $$ (x \cdot 54) \times 12=648 x $$ $\Rightarrow$ total work load. $648 x \div 54 \div 20=0.6 x$ $\Rightarrow$ a woman can finish $0.6 x$ per day. Assume 9 men \& 39 women need $y$ days to finish the work. $$ \begin{aligned} & {[9 x+(39 \cdot 0.6 x)] y=648 x} \\ & \Rightarrow(9 x+23.4 x) y=648 x \\ & \Rightarrow 32.4 x y=648 x \\ & \Rightarrow y=648 x \div(32.4 x)=20 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: two trains 200 m and 150 m long are running on parallel rails at the rate of 40 kmph and 45 kmph respectively . in how much time will they cross each other , if they are running in the same direction ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} (200-150) & =50 \\ 50+150 & =200 \mathrm{~m} \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow$ total distance $$ \begin{aligned} 45 \mathrm{~km}-40 \mathrm{~km}=5 \mathrm{~km} & \\ 5 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr}=5000 \div 60 \div 60 & =\frac{50}{36} \\ & =\frac{25}{18} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow$ the gap between the two train per second. $$ 200 \div \frac{25}{18}=200 \times \frac{18}{25}=8 \times 18=144 $$ seconds

student_process: Assume the number of blue gumball is $x$, and the total number is $y$. $$ \begin{aligned} & \left(\frac{x}{y}\right) \cdot\left(\frac{x}{y}\right)=\frac{16}{49} \\ & \Rightarrow\left(\frac{x^2}{y^2}\right)=\frac{16}{49} \Rightarrow \frac{x}{y}=\sqrt{\frac{16}{49}}=\frac{4}{\eta} \\ & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array}{l} x=4 \\ y=7 \end{array}\right. \end{aligned} $$ $\because \eta-4=3 \Rightarrow$ the number of pink gumball. $\therefore$ the possibility of drawing a pink gumball is $\frac{3}{7}

Problem: a ' s speed is 15 / 13 times that of b . if a and b run a race , what part of the length of the race should a give b as a head start , so that b beats a by 40 % of the length of the race ?
student_process: Assume the length of the race is $x_1 \&$ the length between the two headstart is $x_2$ \& the speed of $b$ is $y$, and the finish time of $b$ is $z$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \left\{\begin{array}{l} y \cdot z=\left(x_1-x_2\right) \\ \frac{15}{13} y \cdot z=0.6 x_1-(2) \end{array}\right. \\ & \Rightarrow \div(2) \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{13}{13}=\frac{\left(x_1-x_2\right)}{0.6 x_1} \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{13}{15} \times \frac{3}{5}=\frac{\left(x_1-x_2\right)}{x_1}=1-\frac{x_2}{x_1} \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{x_2}{x_1}=1-\frac{79}{75}=\frac{36}{75}=\frac{12}{25}=0.48 \\ & \Rightarrow x_2=0,48 x_1  \end{aligned} $$ A: the b's headstart should be ahead of $A$ 's headstart $48 \%$ of the length of the race

Problem: tourist purchased a total of 30 travelers checks in $ 50 and $ 100 denominations . the total worth of the travelers checks is $ 1800 . how many checks of $ 50 denominations can he spend so that average amount ( arithmetic mean ) of the remaining travelers checks is $ 75 ?
student_process: Assume the number of travelers checks in $\$ 50$ is $\chi_{\text {. }}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 50 \cdot x+100(30-x)=1800 \\ & \Rightarrow 50 x+1000-100 x=1800 \\ & \Rightarrow 50 x=3000-1800=1200 \\ & \Rightarrow x=1200 \div 50=24 \end{aligned} $$ $30-24=6 \Rightarrow$ the number of checks in $\$ 100$  Assume he spend $y$ checks in \$50 $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(24-y) \cdot 50+6 \cdot 100}{(24-y+6)}=75 \\ & \Rightarrow 1200-50 y+600=2250-75 y \\ & \Rightarrow 25 y=2250-1800=450 \\ & \Rightarrow y=450 \div 25=18 \end{aligned} $$
concepts_of_the_problem: Arithmetic Mean && Expression and Operations with Symbols

Problem: the average weight of 10 persons increases by 7.2 kg when a new person comes in place of one of them weighing 65 kg . what might be the weight of the new person ?
student_process: Assume the original average weight is $x \mathrm{~kg}_{\mathrm{g}}$ \& the weight of the new person is $y \mathrm{~kg}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(10 x-65+y)}{10}=x+7.2 \\ & \Rightarrow(10 x-65+y)=10(x+7.2) \\ & \Rightarrow y-65=72 \\ & \Rightarrow y=72+65=137 \mathrm{~kg}  \end{aligned} $$

k is a 3 digit number such that the the ratio of the number to the sum of its digits is least . what is the difference between the hundreds and tens digit ?
student_process: Assume $k$ is $(100 x+10 y+z)$ $$ \because \frac{100 x+10 y+z}{x+y+z}=\frac{(x+y+z)+99 x+9 y}{x+y+z}=1+\frac{99 x+9 y}{x+y+z} $$ If we want the minimum of $1+\frac{99 x+9 y}{x+y+z}$, the $z$ must be 9 $$ \frac{100 x+10 y+z}{x+y+z}=\frac{100(x+y+z)-90 y-99 z}{x+y+z}=100-\frac{90 y+99 z}{x+y+z} $$ If we want the minimum of $100-\frac{90 y+99 z}{x+y+z}$ , the $x$ must be 1 $$ \frac{100 x+10 y+z}{x+y+z}=\frac{10(x+y+z)+90 x-9 z}{x+y+z}=10+\frac{90 x-9 z}{x+y+z} $$ If we want the minimum of $10+\frac{90 x-y z}{x+y+z}$, the $y$ must be 9 $\therefore 9-1=8  \quad$ A : 8

Problem: suresh started a business , investing rs . 18000 . after 3 months and 4 months respectively , rohan and sudhir joined him with capitals of 12000 and 9000 . at the end of the year the total profit was rs . 3960 . what is the difference between rohan  s and sudhir  s share in the profit ?
student_process: $18000+12000+9000=39000 \Rightarrow$ total capital $12-3=9 \Rightarrow$ the time rohan have joined until the end of the year. $12-4=8 \Rightarrow$ the time sudhir have joined until the end of the year. the rohan's share in the profit $$ \Rightarrow 3960 \times \frac{12000}{39000} \times \frac{9}{12}=396 \times \frac{1000}{3900} \times 9=66 \times \frac{9000}{650} = 913.85 $$ the sudhir's share in the profit $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 3960 \times \frac{9000}{39000} \times \frac{8}{12}=1300 \times \frac{18000}{39000}=1320 \times \frac{6}{13} = 609.23 \\ & 913.85-609.23=304.62 \end{aligned} $$

student_process: Assume $a \& b$ can to $\frac{x}{18}$ workload per day, $b \& c$ can to $\frac{x}{24}$ workload per day. a sc can to $\frac{x}{16}$ workload per day. a can do $A$ workload per day. $$ \left\{\begin{array}{l} A+B=\frac{x}{18}-0 \\ B+c=\frac{x}{24}-(2) \\ A+C=\frac{x}{16}-(3) \end{array}\right. $$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \text { (1)-(2) } \\ & \Rightarrow A-C=\frac{4 x}{12}-\frac{3 x}{12}=\frac{x}{12}-(4) \\ & \text { (1)+(4) } \\ & \Rightarrow 2 A=\frac{2 x}{\eta_2}+\frac{x}{\eta_2} \Rightarrow 2 A=\frac{3 x}{\eta_2} \Rightarrow A=\frac{x}{48} \\ & A=\frac{x}{48} \text { put int } 0 \text { \& (3) } \\ & \Rightarrow B=\frac{8 x}{144}-\frac{3 x}{144}=\frac{5 x}{144}, C=\frac{4 x}{144}-\frac{1 x}{144}=\frac{x}{144} \\ & A+B+C=\frac{x}{48}+\frac{5 x}{144}+\frac{x}{144}=\frac{3 x}{144}+\frac{6 x}{144}=\frac{9 x}{144}=\frac{x}{16} \\ & \end{aligned} $$ $\frac{x}{16} \cdot 16=x \Rightarrow$ akb\&c can finish together in 16 days

Problem: the average weight of 8 person ' s increases by 2.5 kg when a new person comes in place of one of them weighing 50 kg . what is the weight of the new person ?
student_process: Assume the original average weight of 8 people is $Y \&$ the weight of the new person is $X \mathrm{~kg}$. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(8 y-50+x)}{8}=(y+2,3) \\ & \Rightarrow 8 y-50+x=8 y+20 \\ & \Rightarrow x=20+50=70 \mathrm{~kg}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: in a class of 38 students 26 play football and play 20 long tennis , if 17 play above , many play neither ?
the average age of 15 students of a class is 15 years . out of these , the average age of 4 students is 14 years and that of the other 9 students is 16 years . tee age of the 15 th student is ?
student_process: $15 \times 15=225 \Rightarrow$ total age $4 \times 14+9 \times 16=56+144=200 \Rightarrow$ total age of the other 14 students. $225-200=25 $

Problem: if p is a prime number greater than 3 , find the remainder when p ^ 2 + 16 is divided by 12 .
student_process: the next prime number is 5 $$ \Rightarrow\left(5^2+16\right) \div 12=41 \div 12=3 \cdots 5 $$ then is $\eta$ $$ \Rightarrow\left(\eta^2+16\right) \div 12=65 \div 12=5 \cdots 5 $$ then is 11 $$ \Rightarrow\left(11^2+16\right) \div 12=137 \div 12=11 \cdots 3 $$ $\because$ the above remainder are all 5 $\therefore$ we can conclude that $\left(p^2+16\right) \div 12$ will always give the remainder as 5

Problem: a student chose a number , multiplied it by 5 , then subtracted 275 from the result and got 135 . what was the number he chose ?
student_process: Assume the number is $X$ $$ \begin{aligned} & (x \cdot 5)-275=135 \\ & \Rightarrow 5 x=135+275=410 \\ & \Rightarrow x=410 \div 5=82 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: last year the price range ( per kg ) for 100 varieties of apples in wholesale market was $ 100 . if the prices of each of the 100 varieties increased by 10 percent this year over what it was last year , what is the range of the wholesale prices of the 1000 varieties of apples this year ?
in 10 years , a will be twice as old as b was 10 years ago . if a is now 9 years older than b , the present age of b is ?
student_process: \begin{aligned} & a=b+9 \\ & (a+10)=2 b \\ & \text { put }(a=b+9) \text { into }(a+10)=2 b \\ & \Rightarrow(b+9)+10=2 b \\ & \Rightarrow b+19=2 b \\ & \Rightarrow b=19 \end{aligned}

Problem: nina has exactly enough money to purchase 6 widgets . if the cost of each widget were reduced by $ 1.15 , then nina would have exactly enough money to purchase 8 widgets . how much money does nina have ?
student_process: Assume nina has money $\$ X \&$ the price of every widget is $y$. every $$ \begin{aligned} & \left\{\begin{array}{l} x=6 y-(1) \\ x=8(y-1.15)-(2) \end{array}\right.  \end{aligned} $$ put (1) into (2) $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 6 y=8(y-1.15)=8 y-9.2 \\ & \Rightarrow 8 y-6 y=9.2 \Rightarrow 2 y=9.2 \Rightarrow y=4.6 \\ & \text { put }(y=4.6) \text { into (1) } \\ & \Rightarrow x=6 \cdot 4.6=27.6  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a and b start walking towards each other at 5 am at speed of 4 kmph and 8 kmph . they were initially 36 km apart . at what time do they meet ?
student_process: $4+8=12 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \Rightarrow$ the decrease of distance between $a \& b$. $36 \div 12=3$ hours. 5:00 + hours $=8: 00 $

Problem: how many integers from 1 to 100 ( both inclusive ) have odd number of factors ?
student_process: The all prime numbers have even number of factors. all $x^2$ have odd number of factors. $$ \Rightarrow 1,4,9,16,25,36,49,64,81,100 $$ other number have pairs of factors , so those have even number of factors. According to the above descriptions, we can conclude that there are 10 numbers have odd number of factors.

Problem: a person can swim in still water at 4 km / h . if the speed of water 2 km / h , how many hours will the man take to swim back against the current for 6 km ?
student_process: $4-2=2 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \Rightarrow$ the speed of the man swimming against the current. $6 \div 2=3$ hours.

Problem: what is the sum of the first 15 terms of an a . p whose 11 th and 7 th terms are 5.25 and 3.25 respectively
student_process: $$ \left\{\begin{array}{l} a_{11}=a_1+(11-1) d=5,25 \\ a_7=a_1+(7-1) d=3,25 \end{array}\right. $$ (1) -(2) $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 4 d=5.25-3.25=2 \\ & \Rightarrow d=2 \div 4=\frac{2}{4}=0.5 \\ & \text { put }(f=0,5) \text { into (2) } \\ & \Rightarrow a_7=a_1+(\eta-1) \times(0.5)=3.25 \\ & \Rightarrow a_1+3=3.25 \\ & \Rightarrow a_1=3.25-3=0.25 \\ & a_{15}=a_1+(15-1) d=0.25+14 \times 0.5=0.25+7 \\ & =7.25 \end{aligned} $$ the sum of the first 15 terms is $$ \begin{aligned} \Rightarrow \frac{15\left(a_1+a_{15}\right)}{2}=\frac{15 \times(0.25+7.25)}{2} & =\frac{15 \times 7.5}{2} \\ & =56,25 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: mahesh can do a piece of work in 45 days . he works at it for 20 days and then rajesh finished it in 30 days . how long will y take to complete the work ?
student_process: Assume the workload is $x$ \& mahesh can finish $\frac{x}{45}$ workload per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{45} \times 20=\frac{4 x}{9} \\ & x-\frac{4 x}{9}=\frac{5 x}{9} \end{aligned} $$ rajes finish $\frac{5 x}{9}$ workload in 20 days. $\frac{5 x}{9} \div 30=\frac{5 x}{9} \times \frac{1}{30}=\frac{x}{54} \Rightarrow$ rajes can finish $\frac{x}{34}$ workload per day, $\frac{x}{s 4} \times s 4=x \Rightarrow$ rajes finish the work in 54 days.

Problem: if paint costs $ 3.10 per quart , and a quart covers 20 square feet , how much will it cost to paint the outside of a cube 10 feet on each edge ?
student_process: the surface of the cube is $10 \times 10 \times 6=600$ square feet. $$ 600 \div 20=30 $$ $$ 30 \times(3,10)=93  $$

Problem: a batsman in his 9 th inning makes a score of 75 and their by increasing his average by 7 . what is his average after the 9 th inning ?
student_process: Assume the average before the $9 t h$ inning is $x_1$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{8 x+75}{9}=(x+7) \\ & \Rightarrow 8 x+75=9 x+63 \\ & \Rightarrow x=75-63=12 \\ & 12+7=19 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: in a corporation , 50 percent of the male employees and 40 percent of the female employees are at least 35 years old . if 42 percent of all the employees are at least 35 years old , what fraction of the employees in the corporation are females ?
student_process: Assume the percentage of female employees is $$ \begin{aligned} & x \% \\ & (x \%) \cdot(40 \%)+(1-x \%) \cdot(50 \%)=42 \% \\ & \Rightarrow(0,4 \times \%)+(50 \%)-(0,5 x \%)=42 \% \\ & \Rightarrow(-0,1) x \%=42 \%-50 \%=(-8 \%) \\ & \Rightarrow x \%=(-8 \%) \div(-0,1)=80 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: mary can do a piece of work in 11 days . rosy is 10 % more efficient than mary . the number of days taken by rosy to do the same piece of work is ?
student_process: Assume mary to $\frac{x}{11}$ workload per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{11} \times(1+10 \%)=\frac{x}{11} \times 1.1=\frac{x}{10} \\ & \frac{x}{10} \cdot 10=x \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow$ rosy finish in 10 days

Problem: a is two years older than b who is twice as old as c . if the total ages of a , b and c be 27 . what is the age of b ?
student_process: Assume $b^{\prime}$ s age is $X_1$ $$ \begin{aligned} & (x+2)+x+\frac{1}{2} x=27 \\ & \Rightarrow 2,5 x+2=27 \\ & \Rightarrow 2,5 x=25 \\ & \Rightarrow x=10 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: john and david work at a hospital with 10 other workers . for an internal review , 2 of the 10 workers will be randomly chosen to be interviewed . what is the probability that john and david will both be chosen ?
a batsman in his 11 th inning makes a score of 69 and their by increasing his average by 1 . what is his average after the 11 th inning ?
student_process: Assume the average before the 11 th inning is $X$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{10 x+69}{11}=x+1 \\ & \Rightarrow 10 x+69=11 x+11 \\ & \Rightarrow x=69-11=58 \\ & 58+1=59  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: fresh grapes contain 90 % by weight while dried grapes contain 20 % water by weight . what is the weight of dry grapes available from 10 kg of fresh grapes ?
student_process: $$ 10 \times 0.9=9 $$ $\Rightarrow$ the quantity of water $$ 10-9=1 $$ $\Rightarrow$ the remaining weight. Assume the weight of dry grapes available from $10 \mathrm{~kg}$ of fresh grapes is $x \mathrm{~kg}$. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1-0,2)=1 \mathrm{~kg} \\ & \Rightarrow 0,8 x=1 \mathrm{~kg} \\ & \Rightarrow x=1 \div 0,8=1,25 \mathrm{~kg}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a retailer marks her goods in such a way that the profit made by selling 50 articles is equal to the selling price of 20 articles . what is the percentage of profit made by the retailer ?
student_process: Assume the cost is $x \&$ selling price is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & (y-x) \times 50=20 y \\ & \Rightarrow 50 y-50 x=20 y \\ & \Rightarrow 30 y=50 x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{y}{x}=\frac{50}{30}=\frac{5}{3} = 1.67 \\ & 1.67-1=0,67=67 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a pupil ' s marks were wrongly entered as 83 instead of 53 . due to the average marks for the class got increased by half . the number of pupils in the class is ?
student_process: Assume the number of pupils in this class is $x \&$ the original average marks is $y$ $x y \Rightarrow$ total marks total increase in marks is $$ \begin{aligned} \Rightarrow x & \frac{1}{2}=\frac{x}{2} \\ & \frac{x}{2}=(83-53)=30 \\ \Rightarrow x & =30 \times 2=60  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: you and your friend spent a total of $ 15 for lunch . your friend spent $ 5 more than you . how much did your friend spend on their lunch ?
student_process: Assume your friend spent $\$ X$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x+(x-5)=15 \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x-5=15 \\ \Rightarrow & 2 x=20 \\ \Rightarrow & x=10  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: jerry  s average ( arithmetic mean ) score on the first 3 of 4 tests is 85 . if jerry wants to raise his average by 3 points , what score must he earn on the fourth test ?
a 1100 m long train crosses a tree in 110 sec , how much time will it take to pass a platform 700 m long ?
a rectangular mat has an area of 120 sq . metres and perimeter of 46 m . the length of its diagonal is :
student_process: Assume the length is $X \mathrm{~m}$, $$ \begin{aligned} & (46 \div 2)-x=23-x \Rightarrow \text { width } \\ & x(23-x)=120 \\ & \Rightarrow-x^2+21 x-120=0 \\ & \Rightarrow x^2-23 x+120=0 \\ & \Rightarrow(x-8)(x-15)=0 \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow \because x$ is the long side $$ \therefore x=15 \text { \& width }=23-15=8 $$ $$ \sqrt{15 m}=\sqrt{15^2+8^2}=\sqrt{225+64}=\sqrt{289}=17  $$
concepts_of_the_problem: Area Calculation && Perimeter Calculation && Pythagorean Theorem

Problem: a train 450 metres long is moving at a speed of 25 kmph . it will cross a man coming from the opposite direction at a speed of 2 km per hour in :
student_process: $25+2=27 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \Rightarrow$ the decrease of distance between train and man $$ \begin{aligned} & 27 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \\ & \Rightarrow 27000 \div 60 \div 60 \\ & =7,5 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \\ & 450 \div 7,5=60 \text { seconds } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a can finish a work in 10 days and b can do same work in half the time taken by a . then working together , what part of same work they can finish in a day ?
student_process: Assume the workload is $x \&$ a can finish $\frac{x}{10}$ per day. $\frac{x}{10} \times 2=\frac{x}{5} \Rightarrow b$ can finish per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{10}+\frac{x}{5}=\frac{3 x}{10} \\ & \frac{3 x}{10} \div x=\frac{3}{10} \\end{aligned} $$

Problem: a pupil ' s marks were wrongly entered as 73 instead of 45 . due to that the average marks for the class got increased by half . the number of pupils in the class is :
a river 2 m deep and 45 m wide is flowing at the rate of 7 kmph the amount of water that runs into the sea per minute is ?
a number when divided by a certain divisor left remainder 241 , when twice the number was divided by the same divisor , the remainder was 102 . find the divisor ?
student_process: Assume the number is $x$ \& divisor is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} x \div y & =a \cdots 241 \\ \Rightarrow a y+241 & =x-(1) \\ 2 x \div y & =2 a \cdots 102 \\ \Rightarrow 2 a y & +102=2 x-(2) \\ (1) \times 2 & \Rightarrow 2 a y+482=2 x \\ & \Rightarrow(2 a y+102)+(380)=2 x \end{aligned} $$ $\because 380$ is divisible by $y$, \& leaves remainder 241 when divided by $y$ $\Rightarrow$ means $y>241$ $\therefore y$ is $380 $

Problem: find the length of the wire required to go 12 times round a square field containing 104976 m 2 .
student_process: Assume the length of one side is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 104976=x^2 \\ & \Rightarrow x=\sqrt{104976}=6 \sqrt{2916}=36 \sqrt{81}=324 \end{aligned} $$ $324 \times 4=1296 \Rightarrow$ the length of four side $1296 \times 12=15552 \mathrm{~m} $

Problem: two employees x and y are paid a total of rs . 572 per week by their employer . if x is paid 120 percent of the sum paid to y , how much is y paid per week ?
student_process: Assume y receive $\$ a$ $$ \begin{aligned} & a+(1,2 a)=5 \eta_2 \\ & \Rightarrow 2,2 a=5 \eta_2 \\ & \Rightarrow a=5 \eta_2 \div 2,2=260  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if tim had lunch at $ 50.50 and he gave 20 % tip , how much did he spend ?

in an election , candidate a got 65 % of the total valid votes . if 15 % of the total votes were declared invalid and the total numbers of votes is 560000 , find the number of valid vote polled in favor of candidate ?

susan drove an average speed of 15 miles per hour for the first 40 miles of a tripthen at a average speed of 60 miles / hr for the remaining 20 miles of the trip if she made no stops during the trip what was susan ' s avg speed in miles / hr for the entire trip
student_process: $40 \div 15=\frac{8}{3}$ hours. $20 \div 60=\frac{1}{3}$ hours. $\frac{8}{3}+\frac{1}{3}=\frac{9}{3}=3$ hours $\Rightarrow$ total time. $40+20=60$ miles $\Rightarrow$ total distance. $60 \div 3=20$ miles $/ \mathrm{hr}$.

Problem: out of 9 persons , 8 persons spent rs . 30 each for their meals . the ninth one spent rs . 20 more than the average expenditure of all the 9 . the total money spent by all of them was
student_process: Assume the ninth person spent $\$ x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{30 \times 8+x}{9}+20=x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{30 \times 8+x}{9}=x-20 \\ & \Rightarrow 240+x=9 x-180 \\ & \Rightarrow 8 x=420 \\ & \Rightarrow x=420 \div 8=52.5 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: one fourth of a solution that was 10 % sugar by weight was replaced with by a second solution resulting in a solution that was 16 percent sugar by weight . the second solution was what percent sugar by weight ?
student_process: Assume the second solution is $X \%$ sugar by weight \& first solution is 1 liter. $$ \begin{aligned} & 1 \times 10 \% \times \frac{3}{4}=0,075 \\ & \frac{0,075+(0,25 \cdot x \%)}{0,15+0,25}=16 \% \\ & \Rightarrow 0,075+(0,25 \times \%)=0,16 \\ & \Rightarrow 0,25 x \%=0,085 \\ & \Rightarrow x \%=0,085 \div 0,25=0.34=34 \%  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: at joel  s bookstore , the current inventory is 30 % historical fiction . of the historical fiction books , 30 % are new releases , while 40 % of the other books are new releases . what fraction of all new releases are the historical fiction new releases ?
student_process: Assume there are 100 books, $100 \times 30 \% \times 30 \%=9 \Rightarrow$ new release historical fiction $100 \times(1-30 \%) \times 40 \%=100 \times 10 \% \times 40 \%=28 \Rightarrow \begin{gathered}\text { other new } \\ \text { release }\end{gathered}$ $\frac{9}{9+28}=\frac{9}{37} $

Problem: if a rectangular billboard has an area of 104 square feet and a perimeter of 42 feet , what is the length of each of the shorter sides ?
student_process: Assume the length of shorter side is $X$ $$ 42 \div 2=21 $$ $(21-x) \Rightarrow$ the length of longer side. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(21-x)=104 \\ & \Rightarrow-x^2+21 x-104=0 \\ & \Rightarrow x^2-21 x+104=0 \\ & \Rightarrow(x-8)(x-13)=0 \Rightarrow x=8 \text { or } 13 \end{aligned} $$ $\because X$ is the shorter side $$ \therefore x=8 \text { feet  } $$

Problem: lucia ' s sells kale at x dollar per pound for the first 20 pounds and . 8 x for every subsequent pound . amby ' s price is x per pound for the first 14 pounds and . 9 x for subsequent pounds . what is the minimum number of pounds over 15 for which lucia ' s becomes an equal or better deal ?
student_process: Assume the minimum number of pound is $y$. $$ \begin{aligned} & (x \cdot 20)+(0.8 x) \cdot(y-20)=(x \cdot 14)+(0.9 x) \cdot(y-14) \\ \Rightarrow & 20 x+0.8 x y-16 x=14 x+0.9 x y-12.6 x \\ \Rightarrow & 4 x+0.8 x y=1.4 x+0.9 x y \\ \Rightarrow & 0,1 x y=2,6 x \\ \Rightarrow & 0,1 y=2,6 \\ \Rightarrow & y=26 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: there are 3000 students in a school and among them 20 % of them attends chess class . 40 % of the students who are in the chess class are also enrolled for swimming . no other students are interested in swimming so how many will attend the swimming class if all enrolled attends ?
a fair 2 sided coin is flipped 6 times . what is the probability that tails will be the result at least twice , but not more than 5 times ?
student_process: tails: twice $\Rightarrow c_2^6 \times\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^6=\frac{13}{64}$ three times $\Rightarrow c^6{ }^6 \times\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^6=\frac{20}{64}$ four times $\Rightarrow c_4^6 \times\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^6=\frac{15}{64}$ five times $\Rightarrow c_5^6 \times\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^6=\frac{6}{64}$ $\frac{15}{64}+\frac{20}{64}+\frac{15}{64}+\frac{6}{64}=\frac{56}{64}=\frac{7}{8}$

Problem: in a class , 30 students pass in english and 20 students in math , while some students among these pass in both . how many more students do only english as compared to those doing only maths ?
student_process: Assume the number of students pass both subjects is $X$. Total students: $(30+20-x)=(50-x)$ Only pass English: $30-x$ Only pass math: $20-x$ $$ (30-x)-(20-x)=30-x-20+x=10  $$

Problem: in a can , there is a mixture of milk and water in the ratio 3 : 2 . if the can is filled with an additional 6 liters of milk , the can would be full and the ratio of milk and water would become 2 : 1 . find the capacity of the can ?
student_process: Assume the capacity of the can is $x$ liters. water: $\frac{2}{5} x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \left(\frac{3}{5} x+6\right):\left(\frac{2}{5} x\right)=2: 1 \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{4}{5} x=\frac{3}{5} x+6 \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{1}{5} x=6 \\ & \Rightarrow x=6 \times 5=30 \text { liters  } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a bag contains 7 green and 8 white balls . if two balls are drawn simultaneously , the probability that both are of the same colour is - .
student_process: $7+8=15 \Rightarrow$ total balls two green $$ \Rightarrow \frac{c_2^7}{c_2^{15}}=\frac{21}{105}=\frac{1}{5} $$ two white $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow \frac{c_2^8}{c_2^{15}}=\frac{28}{105}=\frac{4}{15} \\ & \frac{1}{5}+\frac{4}{15}=\frac{3}{15}+\frac{4}{15}=\frac{7}{15} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a bus 75 m long is running with a speed of 21 km / hr . in what time will it pass a woman who is walking at 3 km / hr in the direction opposite to that in which the bus is going ?
student_process: $21+3=24 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \Rightarrow$ the decrease of distance between the bus \& woman. $$ \begin{aligned} & 24 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \\ & =(2400 \div 60 \div 60) \mathrm{m} / \mathrm{sec} \\ & =\frac{20}{3} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \\ & 75 \div \frac{20}{3} \\ & =500 \text { seconds. } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if 14 percent of the students at a certain school went to a camping trip and took more than $ 100 , and 75 percent of the students who went to the camping trip did not take more than $ 100 , what percentage of the students at the school went to the camping trip ?
student_process: Assume the percentage of students went to the camping trip is $\chi \&$ all students at the school is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{(y \cdot 0,14)+(y \cdot x \cdot 0,75)}{y}=x \\ & \Rightarrow(0,14)+(0,75 x)=x \\ & \Rightarrow 0,25 x=0,14 \\ & \Rightarrow x=0,14 \div 0,25=0,56=56 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a family x went for a vacation . unfortunately it rained for 13 days when they were there . but whenever it rained in the mornings , they had clear afternoons and vice versa . in all they enjoyed 11 mornings and 12 afternoons . how many days did they stay there totally ?
student_process: $11+12=23 \Rightarrow$ half try $23-13=10 \Rightarrow$ no rain half day 10 half day $=5$ days. $13+5=18$ days

Problem: the manufacturing cost of a shoe is rs . 210 and the transportation lost is rs . 500 for 100 shoes . what will be the selling price if it is sold at 20 % gains
an alloy is to contain copper and zinc in the ratio 9 : 4 . the zinc required to be melted with 24 kg of copper is ?
student_process: Assume the zinc is $x \mathrm{~kg}$. $$ \begin{aligned} & 9: 4=24: x \\ & \Rightarrow 24 \times 4=9 x \\ & \Rightarrow 96=9 x \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{96}{9}=\frac{32}{3} \mathrm{~kg}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if 5 % more is gained by selling an article for rs . 350 than by selling it for rs . 345 , the cost of the article is
student_process: Assume the cost is $\$ X$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{350-345}{x}=5 \% \\ & \Rightarrow 5=5 \% x \\ & \Rightarrow x=5 \div 0,05=100  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a man took a loan at rate of 12 % per annum simple interest . after 3 years he had to pay 4320 interest . the principal amount borrowed by him was .
student_process: Assume he borrowed $\$ x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(0,12 \times 3)=4320 \\ & \Rightarrow 0,36 x=4320 \\ & \Rightarrow x=4320 \div 0,36=12000 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: of the land owned by a farmer , 90 percent was cleared for planting . of the cleared land , 30 percent was planted with soybeans and 60 percent of the cleared land was planted with wheat . if the remaining 540 acres of cleared land was planted with corn , how many acres did the farmer own ?
student_process: Assume the farmer own $x$ acres. $$ \begin{aligned} & X \cdot(0,9) \cdot(1-30 \%-60 \%)=540 \\ & \Rightarrow(0,9 x) \cdot(0,1)=540 \\ & \Rightarrow 0,09 x=540 \\ & \Rightarrow x=540 \div 0,09=6000 \text { acres }  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: everyone shakes hands with everyone else in a room . total number of handshakes is 78 . number of persons = ?
student_process: Assume there are $X$ people. $$ \begin{aligned} & c_2^x=78 \\ \Rightarrow & \frac{x(x-1)}{2}=78 \\ \Rightarrow & x^2-x=156 \\ \Rightarrow & x^2-x-156=0 \\ \Rightarrow & (x-17)(x+12)=0 \\ \Rightarrow & x=13 \text { or }-12 \text { (negative is impossible) } \\ \Rightarrow & x=13  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: jim  s taxi service charges an initial fee of $ 2.45 at the beginning of a trip and an additional charge of $ 0.35 for each 2 / 5 of a mile traveled . what is the total charge for a trip of 3.6 miles ?

pat , kate , and mark charged a total of 117 hours to a certain project . if pat charged twice as much time to the project as kate and 1 / 3 as much time as mark , how many more hours did mark charge to the project than kate ?
student_process: Assume mark charged $x$ hours. pat: $\frac{1}{3} x$ kate: $\frac{1}{3} x \cdot \frac{1}{2}=\frac{1}{6} x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x+\frac{1}{3} x+\frac{1}{6} x=117 \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{9}{6} x=117 \\ & \Rightarrow x=117 \div \frac{9}{6}=78 \\ & 78-\left(\frac{1}{6} \times 78\right)=78-13=65  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: cole drove from home to work at an average speed of 60 kmh . he then returned home at an average speed of 100 kmh . if the round trip took a total of 2 hours , how many minutes did it take cole to drive to work ?
student_process: Assume the distance is $x \mathrm{~km}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{60}+\frac{x}{100}=2 \mathrm{hr} . \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{8 x}{300}=2 \\ & \Rightarrow 8 x=600 \\ & \Rightarrow x=600 \div 8=75 \\ & 75 \mathrm{~km} \div 60 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr}=\frac{75}{60}=\frac{5}{4}=1.25 \text { hours } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: rs . 800 becomes rs . 956 in 3 years at a certain rate of simple interest . if the rate of interest is increased by 4 % , what amount will rs . 800 become in 3 years .
student_process: Assume the original interest is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 800 \times(1+x \cdot 3)=956 \\ & \Rightarrow 1+3 x=\frac{956}{800}=\frac{239}{200} \\ & \Rightarrow 3 x=\frac{239}{200}-1=\frac{39}{200} \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{13}{200}=\frac{6.5}{100}=6.5 \% \end{aligned} $$ $6,3 \%+4 \%=10,5 \% \Rightarrow$ new interest $$ 800 \times[1+(10,5 \% \times 3)]=800 \times(1,315)=1052 $$

Problem: a bowl of nuts is prepared for a party . brand p mixed nuts are 20 % almonds and brand q ' s deluxe nuts are 25 % almonds . if a bowl contains a total of 68 ounces of nuts , representing a mixture of both brands , and 15 ounces of the mixture are almonds , how many ounces of brand q ' s deluxe mixed nuts are used ?
student_process: Assume using $x$ ounces of brand $q^{\prime}$ s nuts, $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(0,25)+(68-x) \cdot(0,2)=15 \\ \Rightarrow & 0,25 x+13.6-0.2 x=15 \\ \Rightarrow & 0,05 x=1.4 \\ \Rightarrow & x=28 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the cost of 20 articles is equal to selling price of 10 . find the gain or loss percent ?
student_process: Assume the cost is $x \&$ the selling price is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 20 x=10 y \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x=y \\ & \frac{(y-x)}{x}=\frac{2 x-x}{x}=1=100 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: find the value of x from this equation ? 7 ( x - 1 ) = 21
albert is 2 times mary  s age and 4 times as old as betty . mary is 10 years younger than albert . how old is betty ?
student_process: Assume betty is $x$ years old, albert: $4 x$ mary : $2 x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 2 x+10=4 x \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x=10 \\ & \Rightarrow x=5 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if the given two numbers are respectively 7 % and 28 % of a third number , then what percentage is the first of the second ?
student_process: Assume the third number is $x$. $$ \frac{7 \% x}{28 \% x}=\frac{0.01 x}{0.28 x}=\frac{7}{28}=\frac{1}{4}=25 \% $$

Problem: if 30 % of 100 is greater than 50 % of a number by 10 , then the number is ?
student_process: Assume the number is $x_1$ $$ \begin{aligned} & (100 \times 30 \%)=50 \% x+10 \\ & \Rightarrow 30=0,5 x+10 \\ & \Rightarrow 20=0,5 x \\ & \Rightarrow x=20 \div 0,5=40  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if m is an integer such that ( - 2 ) ^ 2 m = 2 ^ ( 12 - m ) then m = ?
student_process: $$ \begin{gathered} (-2)^{2 m}=2^{(12-m)} \\ \because(-2)^{2 m}=2^{(12-m)} \end{gathered} $$ $\therefore 2 \mathrm{~m}$ is even, $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow 2^{2 m}=2^{(12-m)} \\ & \Rightarrow 2 m=12-m \\ & \Rightarrow 3 m=12 \\ & \Rightarrow m=4  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a man can row 7 璽 翻 kmph in still water . if in a river running at 1.5 km / hr an hour , it takes him 50 minutes to row to a place and back , how far off is the place ?
student_process: $7+1.5=8.5 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr} \Rightarrow$ row with current $7-1.5=5.5 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{mm} \Rightarrow$ row against current Assume the distance is $X \mathrm{~km}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{8.5}+\frac{x}{5.5}=\frac{50}{60} \text { hour } \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{11 x}{93.5}+\frac{17 x}{93.5}=\frac{5}{6} \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{28 x}{93.5}=\frac{5}{6} \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{5}{6} \div \frac{28}{93.5}=\frac{467.5}{168}=\frac{935}{336} \mathrm{~km} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: 2 cow  s and 5 goats are brought for rs . 1050 . if the average price of a goat be rs . 90 . what is the average price of a cow .
a shopkeeper loses 15 % , if an article is sold for $ 102 . what should be the selling price of the article to gain 20 % ?
student_process: Assume the cost is $x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1-15 \%)=102 \\ & \Rightarrow 0.85 x=102 \\ & \Rightarrow x=102 \div(0.85)=120 \\ & 120 \times(1+20 \%) \\ & =120 \times 1.2 \\ & =144 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: two persons a and b can complete a piece of work in 30 days and 45 days respectively . if they work together , what part of the work will be completed in 6 days ?
student_process: Assume the workload is $x_1$ $\frac{x}{3} \Rightarrow a$ can do per day. $\frac{x}{45} \Rightarrow b$ can do per day. $\frac{x}{30}+\frac{x}{45}=\frac{5 x}{90}=\frac{x}{18} \Rightarrow a \& b$ can to together per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{18} \times 6=\frac{x}{3} \\ & \frac{x}{3} \div x=\frac{1}{3} \end{aligned} $$

Problem: working alone at its constant rate , machine a produces x boxes in 10 minutes and working alone at its constant rate , machine b produces 2 x boxes in 5 minutes . how many minutes does it take machines a and b , working simultaneously at their respective constant rates , to produce 4 x boxes ?
student_process: $\frac{x}{10} \Rightarrow$ machine a can produce per minute. $\frac{2 x}{5} \Rightarrow$ machine $b$ can produce per minute. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{10}+\frac{2 x}{5}=\frac{5 x}{10}=\frac{1}{2} x \\ & \because \frac{1}{2} x \cdot 8=4 x \end{aligned} $$ $\therefore$ They need 8 minutes to produce $4 X$ boxes.

Problem: a man can row upstream at 20 kmph and downstream at 60 kmph , and then find the speed of the man in still water ?
student_process: Assume the speed of the man in still water is $\chi \&$ \& the speed of current is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & (x-y)=20-0 \\ & (x+y)=60-0 \\ & (1)+(2) \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x=80 \\ & \Rightarrow x=40 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a vessel of capacity 30 litres is fully filled with pure milk . nine litres of milk is removed from the vessel and replaced with water . nine litres of the solution thus formed is removed and replaced with water . find the quantity of pure milk in the final milk solution ?
student_process: $30-9=21 \Rightarrow$ remaining milk $$ \frac{21}{30}=\frac{7}{10}=70 \% $$ $9 \times 70 \%=6,3 \Rightarrow$ removed milk $21-6.3=14.7$ liters $\Rightarrow$ final amount of milk

Problem: if the radius of a circle is decreased 50 % , what happens to the area ?
student_process: Assume the ordinary radius is $x$. Original area: $x^2 \pi$ New area: $\left(\frac{1}{2} x\right)^2 \pi=\frac{1}{4} x^2 \pi$ $\left(\frac{1}{4} x^2 \pi\right) \div\left(x^2 \pi\right)=\frac{1}{4}$

Problem: if the simple interest on a certain amount in at 4 % rate 5 years amounted to rs . 2160 less than the principal . what was the principal ?
student_process: Assume the principal is $X$. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1+4 \% \times 5)=2160 \\ \Rightarrow & x \cdot(1+20 \%)=2160 \\ \Rightarrow & 1.2 x=2160 \\ \Rightarrow & x=1800 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: stacy has a 33 page history paper due in 3 days . how many pages per day would she have to write to finish on time ?
jennifer had $ 150 to spend on herself . she spent 1 / 5 of the money on a sandwich , 1 / 6 for a ticket to a museum , and 1 / 2 of it on a book . how much money does jennifer have left over ?

two bullet trains of equal lengths take 10 seconds and 30 seconds respectively to cross a telegraph post . if the length of each bullet train be 120 metres , in what time ( in seconds ) will they cross each other travelling in opposite direction ?
student_process: $\left.\begin{array}{l}120 \div 10=12 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \\ 120 \div 30=4 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec}\end{array}\right\}$ speed of two train $12+4=16 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \Rightarrow$ total speed when they travel in opposite direction $120 \div 16=\frac{15}{2}=7.5$ seconds

Problem: the average salary of a person for the months of january , february , march and april is rs . 8000 and that for the months february , march , april and may is rs . 8200 . if his salary for the month of may is rs . 6500 , find his salary for the month of january ?
student_process: $\begin{aligned} 8000 \times 4=32000 \Rightarrow & \text { total salary of January, February, } \\ & \text { march\& April }\end{aligned}$ march \& April $8200 \times 4=32800 \Rightarrow$ total salary of February, March, April \& May. $32800-6500=26300 \Rightarrow$ total salary of February, March \& April $32000-26300=5700 $

Problem: a bowl contains equal numbers of red , orange , green , blue , and yellow candies . kaz eats all of the green candies and half of the orange ones . next , he eats half of the remaining pieces of each color . finally , he eats red and yellow candies in equal proportions until the total number of remaining candies of all colors equals 24 % of the original number . what percent of the red candies remain ?
student_process: Assume the number of per color is x \begin{aligned} & (? x) \times 2+\frac{1}{4} x+\frac{1}{2} x=(0.24) \cdot(5 x) \\ & \Rightarrow(? x) \times 2=1.2 x-0.5 x-0.25 x=0.45 x \\ & \Rightarrow ? x=(0.45 x) \div 2=0.225 x \\ & \Rightarrow ?=0.225=22.5 \% \end{aligned}

Problem: solution x is 30 % chemical a and 70 % chemical b by volume . solution y is 40 % chemical a and 60 % chemical b by volume . if a mixture of x and y is 36 % chemical a , what percent of the mixture is solution x ?
student_process: Assume the mixture is 1 liter $\& Z$ percentage of mixture is solution $x_1$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{z \cdot(0,3)+(1-z) \cdot(0,4)}{1}=36 \% \\ & \Rightarrow 0,3 z+0,4-0,4 z=0,36 \\ & \Rightarrow 0,1 z=0,04 \\ & \Rightarrow z=0,04 \div 0,1=0,4=40 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the cost price of an article is 36 % of the marked price . calculate the gain percent after allowing a discount of 20 % .
student_process: Assume the marked price is $X$ cost price : $0.36 x$ $$ \begin{aligned} & X \cdot(1-20 \%) \\ & =0.8 x \\ & \frac{(0.8 x-0.36 x)}{0.8 x}=\frac{0.44 x}{0.8 x}=\frac{44}{80}=\frac{11}{20} \\ & =55 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: set a { 3 , 3,3 , 4,5 , 5,5 } has a standard deviation of 1 . what will the standard deviation be if every number in the set is multiplied by 2 ?

a bank pays interest to its customers on the last day of the year . the interest paid to a customer is calculated as 10 % of the average monthly balance maintained by the customer . john is a customer at the bank . on the last day , when the interest was accumulated into his account , his bank balance doubled to $ 5080 . what is the average monthly balance maintained by john in his account during the year ?
student_process: Assume the average monthly balance is $X$. $5080 \div 2=2540 \Rightarrow$ the interest $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(10 \%)=2540 \\ & \Rightarrow x=2540 \div 0.1=25400  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a man has $ 480 in the denominations of one - dollar , 5 - dollar notes and 10 - dollar . the number of dollars of each denomination is equal . what is the total number of dollar that he has ?
student_process: Assume the number of dollars of each denomination is $X$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 10 x+5 x+x=480 \\ & \Rightarrow 16 x=480 \\ & \Rightarrow x=30 \\ & 30 \times 3=90 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the cost price of a radio is rs . 1500 and it was sold for rs . 1200 , find the loss % ?
in a school of 850 boys , 40 % of muslims , 28 % hindus , 10 % sikhs and the remaining of other communities . how many belonged to the other communities ?
an woman swims downstream 64 km and upstream 24 km taking 8 hours each time ; what is the speed of the current ?
student_process: Assume the speed of the current is $x \&$ the speed of the woman is $Y$. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{64}{(x+y)}=8 \\ & \Rightarrow 64=8(x+y)-(1) \\ & \frac{24}{(y-x)}=8 \\ & \Rightarrow 24=8(y-x)-(2) \\ &(1)-(2) \\ & \Rightarrow 40=16 x \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{40}{16}=\frac{5}{2}=2.5 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a man can row upstream at 32 kmph and downstream at 48 kmph , and then find the speed of the man in still water ?
student_process: Assume the speed of the man in still water is $x \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{mr}$ \& the speed of the current is $y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr} . \\ & \left\{\begin{array}{l} x+y=48 \\ x-y=32 \end{array}\right. \\ & \begin{array}{l} 10+(2) \\ \Rightarrow 2 x=80 \end{array} \\ & \Rightarrow x=40 \mathrm{~km} / \mathrm{hr}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a train passes a man standing on a platform in 8 seconds and also crosses the platform which is 267 metres long in 20 seconds . the length of the train ( in metres ) is :
student_process: Assume the length of the train is $x$ m & its speed is $y \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec}$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{x}{8}=y \\ & \Rightarrow x=8 y-\text { (1) } \\ & \frac{(267+x)}{20}=y \\ & \Rightarrow 267+x=20 y \text {-(2) } \\ & \text { put (1) into (2) } \\ & \Rightarrow 267+8 y=20 y \\ & \Rightarrow 267=12y \\ & \Rightarrow y=267 \div 12=22.25 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{sec} \\ & x=8 \cdot(22.25)=178 \mathrm{~m}  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a $ 500 investment and a $ 1,500 investment have a combined yearly return of 8.5 percent of the total of the two investments . if the $ 500 investment has a yearly return of 7 percent , what percent yearly return does the $ 1 , 500 investment have ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & (500+1500) \times(8.5 \%) \\ & =2000 \times 0.085 \\ & =170 \Rightarrow \text { total return } \\ & 500 \times 7 \% \\ & =35 \\ & 170-35=135 \end{aligned} $$ Assume the yearly return of $\$ 1500$ is $\times \%$ $$ \begin{aligned} & 1500 \cdot x=135 \\ & \Rightarrow x=135 \div 1500=\frac{9}{100}=9 \% \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if daily wages of a man is double to that of a woman , how many men should work for 25 days to earn rs . 14400 ? given that wages for 40 women for 30 days are rs . 21600 .
student_process: Assume the daily wage of women is $X$. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot 40 \cdot 30=21600 \\ & \Rightarrow x=2160 \div 30 \div 40=720 \div 40=18 \\ & 18 x_2=36 \Rightarrow \text { daily wage of men. } \end{aligned} $$ Assume need $y$ men to earn 14400 in 25 days. $$ \begin{aligned} & 36 \cdot y \cdot 25=14400 \\ & \Rightarrow y=14400 \div 36 \div 25=16  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a can do a work in 14 days and working together a and b can do the same work in 10 days . in what time can b alone do the work ?
student_process: Assume the workload is $X$. $\frac{x}{14} \Rightarrow$ a can to per day. Assume $b$ can to $y$ per day, $$ \begin{aligned} & \left(\frac{x}{14}+y\right) \times 10=x \\ \Rightarrow & 10 y=x-\frac{10 x}{14}=\frac{4 x}{14}=\frac{2 x}{7} \\ \Rightarrow & y=\frac{2 x}{70}=\frac{x}{35} \\ & \frac{x}{35} \times 35=x \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow b$ need 35 days to finish the work alone

Problem: if a ^ 3 is divisible by 240 what is the least possible value of integer a ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & 240=2^4 \times 3 \times 5 \\ & \text { if } a=2 \times 3 \times 5 \Rightarrow a^3=2^3 \times 3^3 \times 5^3 \end{aligned} $$ $\Rightarrow$ can't be divisible by 240 if $a=2^2 \times 3 \times 5 \Rightarrow a^3=2^6 \times 3^3 \times 5^3$ $\Rightarrow$ can be divisible by 240 $$ \Rightarrow a=60  $$

Problem: a part - time employee whose hourly wage was decreased by 20 percent decided to increase the number of hours worked per week so that the employee ' s total income did not change . by what percent w should the number of hours worked be increased ?
student_process: Assume the original wage is $x$ \& the percentage of hours he should increase is $Y$. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1-20 \%) \cdot(1+y)=x \\ & \Rightarrow 0,8 x \cdot(1+y)=x \\ & \Rightarrow(1+y)=\frac{10}{8} \\ & \Rightarrow y=\frac{10}{8}-1=\frac{2}{8}=25 \% \end{aligned} $$
concepts_of_the_problem: Direct Proportion and Inverse Proportion && Ratio Calculation

Problem: a box measuring 49 inches long by 42 inches wide by 14 inches deep is to be filled entirely with identical cubes . no space is to be left unfilled . what is the smallest number of cubes that can accomplish this objective ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & 49 \times 42 \times 14 \\ & =\eta^2 \times(7 \times 2 \times 3) \times(2 \times 7)=2^2 \times 3 \times 7^4 \end{aligned} $$ Assume the length of one side of the cube is $x$. $288 / 2$ can be divided by $x^3$ if $x=2 \times 3 \times \eta \Rightarrow x^3=2^3 \times 3^3 \times \eta^3>2^2 \times 3 \times \eta^4$ if $x=\eta \Rightarrow x^3=\eta^3=343,288 / 2$ can be derided by 343 $$ 28812 \div 343=84  $$

Problem: a certain bus driver is paid a regular rate of $ 16 per hour for any number of hours that does not exceed 40 hours per week . for any overtime hours worked in excess of 40 hours per week , the bus driver is paid a rate that is 75 % higher than his regular rate . if last week the bus driver earned $ 1200 in total compensation , how many total hours did he work that week ?
student_process: Assume he work $x$ hours. $$ \begin{aligned} & (16 \times 40)+[40 \times(1+75 \%)] \times(x-40)=1200 \\ & \Rightarrow 640+70(x-40)=1200 \\ & \Rightarrow 70 x-2800=560 \\ & \Rightarrow 70 x=3360 \\ & \Rightarrow x=48  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the average mark of the students of a class in a particular exam is 80 . if 5 students whose average mark in that exam is 20 are excluded , the average mark of the remaining will be 92 . find the number of students who wrote the exam .
student_process: Assume the number of students who wrote the exam is $x$. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{80 x-20 \cdot 5}{(x-5)}=92 \\ \Rightarrow & 80 x-100=92 x-460 \\ \Rightarrow & 12 x=360 \\ \Rightarrow & x=30 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: in a factory , an average of 50 tv ' s are produced per day for the fist 25 days of the months . a few workers fell ill for the next 5 days reducing the daily avg for the month to 43 sets / day . the average production per day for day last 5 days is ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & 43 \times 30-50 \times 25 \\ & =1290-1250 \end{aligned} $$ $=40 \Rightarrow$ the total production for the last $S$ days. $$ 40 \div 5=8  $$

Problem: a , b , c , d and e are 5 consecutive points on a straight line . if bc = 2 cd , de = 4 , ab = 5 and ac = 11 , what is the length of ae ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & a c-a b=b c \\ & \Rightarrow 11-5=6 \\ & b c=2 c d \\ & \Rightarrow 6=2 c d \\ & \Rightarrow c d=3 \end{aligned} $$ $a e=a b+b c+c d+d e$ $=5+6+3+4=18$

Problem: operation # is defined as : a # b = 4 a ^ 2 + 4 b ^ 2 + 8 ab for all non - negative integers . what is the value of ( a + b ) + 4 , when a # b = 100 ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & 4 a^2+4 b^2+8 a b=100 \\ \Rightarrow & a^2+b^2+2 a b=25 \\ \Rightarrow & (a+b)^2=25 \\ \Rightarrow & a+b= \pm \sqrt{25}= \pm 5 \end{aligned} $$ $\because$ question said for all non-negative integers. $$ \begin{aligned} & \therefore a+b=5 \\ & (a+b)+4 \\ & =5+4 \\ & =9 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a trader sells 66 meters of cloth for rs . 660 at the profit of rs . 5 per metre of cloth . what is the cost price of one metre of cloth ?
student_process: Assume the cost of one metre of cloth is $x$. $$ \begin{aligned} & 5 \times 66=330 \Rightarrow \text { Total profit } \\ & (660-330) \div 66=x \\ & \Rightarrow 330 \div 66=x \\ & \Rightarrow x=5  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a group of men decided to do a work in 10 days , but 5 of them became absent . if the rest of the group did the work in 12 days , find the original number of men ?
student_process: Assume the original number of men is $x \&$ the workload is $y$ $\frac{y}{10 x} \Rightarrow a$ person can to per day. $$ \begin{aligned} & \frac{y}{10 x} \cdot 10 \cdot x=\frac{y}{10 x} \cdot 12 \cdot(x-5) \\ & \Rightarrow y=\frac{12 y(x-5)}{10 x} \\ & \div y \\ & \Rightarrow 1=\frac{12(x-5)}{10 x} \end{aligned} $$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \cdot 10 x \\ & \Rightarrow 10 x=12 x-60 \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x=60 \\ & \Rightarrow x=30  \end{aligned} $$

Problem: in the x - y plane , point ( x , y ) is a lattice point if both x and y are integers . a square has a center at ( 0 , 0 ) and side = 4 . some points , such as the center ( 0 , 0 ) , are inside the square , but a point such as ( 0 , 2 ) is on the square but not in the square . how many lattice points are in the square ?
student_process: 4 corners on the square $$ \Rightarrow(2,2),(-2,2),(2,-2),(-2,-2) $$ in the square $$ \begin{aligned} \Rightarrow & (0,0),(0,1),(0,-1),(1,0),(1,1),(1,-1),(-1,0),(-1,-1) \\ & (-1,1)  \end{aligned} $$ A: 9
concepts_of_the_problem: Graphs of Cartesian Coordinates and Linear Equations

Problem: a rectangular field is to be fenced on three sides leaving a side of 20 feet uncovered . if the area of the field is 10 sq . feet , how many feet of fencing will be required ?
student_process: Assume the short side is $X$ feet. $$ \begin{aligned} & 20 \cdot x=10 \\ & \Rightarrow x=10=20=0,5 \text { feet } \\ & (0,5 \times 2)+20 \\ & =21 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: at joes steakhouse the hourly wage for a chef is 25 % greater than that of a dishwasher , and the hourly wage of a dishwasher is half as much as the hourly wage of a manager . if a managers wage is $ 8.50 per hour , how much less than a manager does a chef earn each hour ?
student_process: Assume the chef can earn $\$ x$ per hour. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1-25 \%) \div \frac{1}{2}=8.50 \\ & \Rightarrow 0.75 x \cdot 2=8.50 \\ & \Rightarrow 1,5 x=8.50 \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{8.5}{1.5}=\frac{17}{3} \\ & 8.50-\frac{17}{3}=\frac{17}{2}-\frac{17}{3}=\frac{51}{6}-\frac{34}{6}=\frac{17}{6} = 2.83 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: 140 is what percent of 40 ?
at a wedding reception , 125 guests ate chicken and 75 guests ate beef . if exactly 100 guests ate only one of the two types of meat , how many guests ate both types of meat ?
student_process: Assume $X$ people only eat chicken \& y people eat both \& $z$ people only eat beef. $$ \begin{aligned} & \left\{\begin{array}{l} x+y=125-10 \\ y+z=75 \\ x+z=100 \end{array}\right. \\ & (1)-(3) \\ & \Rightarrow y-z=25-(3) \\ & \text { (2) }+ \text { (4) } \\ & \Rightarrow 2 y=100 \\ & \Rightarrow y=100 \div 2=50 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: the average of 10 numbers is calculated as 15 . it is discovered later on that while calculating the average one number , namely 36 was wrongly read as 26 . the correct average is :
if jake loses 8 pounds , he will weigh twice as much as his sister kendra . together they now weigh 281 pounds . what is jake  s present weight , in pounds ?
student_process: Assume the weight of jake is $\chi$ pounds. $(x-8) \div 2 \Rightarrow$ the weight of his sister, $$ \begin{aligned} & x+[(x-8) \div 2]=281 \\ & \Rightarrow x+0.5 x-4=281 \\ & \Rightarrow 1.5 x=285 \\ & \Rightarrow x=190 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: thirty percent of the members of a swim club have passed the lifesaving test . among the members who havenotpassed the test , 5 have taken the preparatory course and 30 have not taken the course . how many members are there in the swim club ?
student_process: Assume there are $x$ members. $$ \begin{aligned} & x \cdot(1-30 \%)=30+5 \\ & \Rightarrow 0.7 x=35 \\ & \Rightarrow x=50 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a can give b 70 meters start and c 200 meters start in a kilometer race . how much start can b give c in a kilometer race ?
student_process: Assume the race is low meters. $\Rightarrow \begin{cases}a & \text { runs } 1000 \text { meters } \\ b & \text { runs } 990 \text { meters } \\ c & \text { runs } 800 \text { meters }\end{cases}$ when $b$ runs 1000 meters $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow c \text { run }: \frac{1000 \times 800}{930}=\frac{80000}{93} \fallingdotseq 880,22 \\ & 1000-860,22=139.78 \text { meters } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: if jake loses 20 pounds , he will weigh twice as much as his sister . together they now weigh 224 pounds . what is jake  s present weight , in pounds ?
student_process: Assume the weight of Jake is $X$ pounds. $(x-20) \div 2 \Rightarrow$ the weight of his sister. $$ \begin{aligned} & x+[(x-20) \div 2]=224 \\ & \Rightarrow x+0,5 x-10=224 \\ & \Rightarrow 1,5 x=234 \\ & \Rightarrow x=156 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: in the rectangular coordinate system , if the line x = 8 y + 5 passes through points ( m , n ) and ( m + 2 , n + p ) , what is the value of p ?
student_process: \begin{aligned} & x=8 y+5 \text { through }(m, n) \&(m+2, n+p) \\ & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array}{l} m=8 n+5-1) \\ (m+2)=8(n+p)+5-(2) \end{array}\right. \\ & \text { put } 10 \text { into }(2) \\ & \Rightarrow(8 n+5)+2=8(n+p)+5 \\ & \Rightarrow 8 n+7=8 n+8 p+5 \\ & \Rightarrow 8 p=2 \\ & \Rightarrow p=\frac{1}{4}=0.25 \end{aligned}
concepts_of_the_problem: Graphs of Cartesian Coordinates and Linear Equations

Problem: a boat m leaves shore a and at the same time boat b leaves shore b . they move across the river . they met at 500 yards away from a and after that they met 300 yards away from shore b without halting at shores . find the distance between the shore a & b .
student_process: Assume the distance between shore $a \& b$ is $x$. \& the speed of $\mathrm{m}$ is $y$ yards per hour \& the speed of $b$ is $z$ yards per hour. $t=$ the time past $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array}{l} y t_1=500 \\ z t_1=(x-500) \\ y t_2=x+300 \\ z t_2=x+(x-300) \end{array}\right. \\ & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array}{l} \frac{y t_2}{y t_1}=\frac{t_2}{t_1}=\frac{x+300}{500} \\ \frac{z t_2}{z t_1}=\frac{t_2}{t_1}=\frac{2 x-300}{x-500} \end{array}\right. \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{2 x-300}{x-500}=\frac{x+300}{500} \\ & \Rightarrow 1000 x-150000=x^2-200 x-150000 \\ & \Rightarrow x^2=1200 x \\ & \Rightarrow x=1200  \quad A: 1200 \text { yards } \end{aligned} $$

Problem: car q and car y traveled the same 80 - mile route . if car q took 2 hours and car y traveled at an average speed that was 50 percent faster than the average speed of car q , how many hours did it take car y to travel the route ?
two employees x and y are paid a total of rs . 506 per week by their employer . if x is paid 120 percent of the sum paid to y , how much is y paid per week ?
student_process: \begin{aligned} & x=1.2 y \\ & x+y=506 \\ \Rightarrow & 1.2 y+y=506 \\ \Rightarrow & 2.2 y=506 \\ \Rightarrow & y=506 \div 2.2=230 \end{aligned}

Problem: a garrison of 1850 men has provisions for 28 days . at the end of 12 days , a reinforcement arrives , and it is now found that the provisions will last only for 10 days more . what is the reinforcement ?
student_process: Assume the total provisions is $x \&$ the number of reinforcement is $y$ men. $$ \begin{aligned} & 1850 \cdot 28=x \\ & \Rightarrow x=51800 \\ & 51800-(1850 \times 12) \\ & =51800-22200 \\ & =29600 \\ & 29600=(1850+y) \cdot 10 \\ & \Rightarrow 2960=1850+y \\ & \Rightarrow y=2960-1850=1110 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: for the positive integers x , x + 2 , x + 4 , x + 7 , and x + 32 , the mean is how much greater than the median ?

Problem: the length of the bridge , which a train 170 meters long and travelling at 45 km / hr can cross in 30 seconds , is ?

student_process: $$ 8 \text { meters }=(\text { radius }) \times 2 \times \pi \Rightarrow \text { radius }=\frac{4}{\pi} \text { meters. } $$ 10 meters $=($ radius $) \times 2 \times \pi \Rightarrow$ radius $=\frac{5}{\pi}$ meters the capacity of a $$ \Rightarrow\left(\frac{4}{\pi}\right)^2 \pi \times 9=\frac{16}{\pi} \times 9=\frac{144}{\pi} $$ the capacity of $b$ $$ \begin{aligned} \Rightarrow\left(\frac{5}{\pi}\right)^2 \pi \times 8 & =\frac{25}{\pi} \times 8=\frac{200}{\pi} \\ & \frac{144}{\pi} \div \frac{200}{\pi}=\frac{144}{200}=\frac{72}{100}=72 \% \end{aligned} $$

Assume they need $y$ days to finish. $$ \begin{aligned} & {\left[\left(\frac{x}{96} \cdot(6)+\left(\frac{x}{144} \cdot 12\right)\right] y=x\right.} \\ & \Rightarrow\left(\frac{x}{6}+\frac{x}{12}\right) y=x \\ & \Rightarrow \frac{x}{4} y=x \\ & \Rightarrow y=x \div \frac{x}{4}=4 \end{aligned} $$

Problem: a train with 120 wagons crosses john who is going in the same direction , in 36 seconds . it travels for half an hour from the time it starts ove ( who is also riding on his horse ) coming from the opposite direction in 24 seconds . in how much time after the train has crossed the mike do the john meets to mike ? rtaking the john ( he is riding on the horse ) before it starts overtaking the mike
student_process: Assume the speed of train is $x$, john is $y$, mike is $z$, the length of the train is a $$ \begin{aligned} & \left\{\begin{array}{l} \frac{a}{x-y}=36 \Rightarrow a=36(x-y) \\ \frac{a}{x+z}=24 \Rightarrow a=24(x+z) \end{array}\right. \\ & \Rightarrow 36 x-36 y=24 x+24 z \\ & \Rightarrow 3 y+2 z=0 \end{aligned} $$ traveling length for half hour. $$ \begin{aligned} \Rightarrow & 1800 x \& 1800 y \\ & 1800(x-y)=1800(3 y+2 z-y)=1800(2 y+2 z)=3600(y+z) \end{aligned} $$ the distance between john \& mike is $$ \Rightarrow(y+z) $$ $[3600(y+z)] \div(y+z)=3600$ seconds. $3600-24=3576$ seconds

Problem: 14 . the sum and the product of two numbers are 25 and 144 respectively , the difference of the number is ?
student_process: Assume the two number is $x \& y$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \left\{\begin{array}{l} x+y=25 \\ x y=144 \end{array}\right. \\ & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array}{l} x=25-y-1 \\ x y=144-0 \end{array}\right. \\ & \text { put (1) into (2) } \\ & \Rightarrow(25-y) y=144 \\ & \Rightarrow y^2-25 y+144=0 \\ & \Rightarrow(y-16)(y-9)=0 \\ & \Rightarrow y=16 \text { or } 9 \\ & \Rightarrow\left\{\begin{array} { l } { x = 1 6 } \\ { y = 9 } \end{array} \text { or } \left\{\begin{array}{l} x=9 \\ y=16 \end{array}\right.\right. \\ & 16-9=7\end{aligned} $$

Problem: what is the sum of all possible solutions to | x - 3 | ^ 2 + | x - 3 | = 20 ?
student_process: $$ \begin{aligned} & |x-3|^2+|x-3|=20 \\ & x \geqq 3 \\ & \Rightarrow(x-3)^2+(x-3)-20=0 \\ & \Rightarrow 2 x^2-5 x-14=0 \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{5 \pm \sqrt{25+112}}{4} \\ & \because \frac{5-\sqrt{177}}{4}<3 \\ & \therefore x=\frac{5+\sqrt{177}}{4} \\ & \end{aligned} $$ $x<3$ $$ \begin{aligned} & \Rightarrow(3-x)^2+(3-x)-20=0 \\ & \Rightarrow-x^2-7 x-8=0 \\ & \stackrel{\times (-1)}{\Rightarrow} x^2+7 x+8=0 \\ & \Rightarrow x=\frac{-7 \pm \sqrt{49-32}}{2}=\frac{-7 \pm \sqrt{17}}{2} \end{aligned} $$ the sum of all possible solutions $$ \begin{gathered} \Rightarrow\left(\frac{5+\sqrt{137}}{4}\right)+\left(\frac{-7+\sqrt{17}}{2}\right)+\left(\frac{-7-\sqrt{17}}{2}\right)=\frac{5+\sqrt{137}}{4}+\frac{-28}{4} \\ =\frac{-23+\sqrt{117}}{4} \quad A: \frac{-23+\sqrt{137}}{4} \end{gathered} $$

Problem: a starts business with rs . 3500 and after 5 months , b joins with a as his partner . after a year , the profit is divided in the ratio 2 : 3 . what is b ' s contribution in the capital ?

Problem: shopkeeper rise price by 33 % and gives successive discount of 10 % and 15 % . what is overall % gain or loss ?
